The Supreme Court has fixed May 24 for judgment in the appeals over the disqualification of candidates of the All Progressives Congress (APC) in Zamfara State. A five-member panel of justices presided by the acting Chief Justice of Nigeria, Justice Ibrahim Tanko Muhammad on Thursday fixed the date after listening to the arguments of counsels in the matter. The Governor Abdulazeez Yari faction of the APC, which emerged after the October 3, 2018 primary of the party had asked the apex court to set aside the judgement of the Court of Appeal in Sokoto in an appeal by the Kabir Marafa faction of the party challenging the outcome of the primary. But while counsel to the Marafa-faction, Mike Ozekhome (SAN) urged the apex court to dismiss the appeal for being incompetent, Yari’s counsel Lateef Fagbemi (SAN) asked the panel to dismiss the objection. Details later….  Zamfara APC: Legal logjam as S/Court fixes hearing May 16 2019 polls: Supreme Court to decide Rivers appeals tomorrow Zamfara APC: Supreme Court fixes May 16 for hearing of motions Dear Esteemed reader, As part of our drive to keep improving the content of our newspaper, we are conducting a readership survey to enable us serve you better. Kindly take two minutes of your time to fill in this questionnaire. Thank you for your time. Click here to begin